26. Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array (Easy LeetCode)
Hint
Given an integer array nums sorted in non-decreasing order, remove the duplicates in-place such that each unique element appears only once. The relative order of the elements should be kept the same.
Consider the number of unique elements in nums to be kâ€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹. After removing duplicates, return the number of unique elements k.

The first k elements of nums should contain the unique numbers in sorted order. The remaining elements beyond index k - 1 can be ignored.

Custom Judge:
The judge will test your solution with the following code:

int[] nums = [...]; // Input array
int[] expectedNums = [...]; // The expected answer with correct length

int k = removeDuplicates(nums); // Calls your implementation
assert k == expectedNums.length;
for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
    assert nums[i] == expectedNums[i];
}
If all assertions pass, then your solution will be accepted.

Example 1:
Input: nums = [1,1,2]
Output: 2, nums = [1,2,_]
Explanation: Your function should return k = 2, with the first two elements of nums being 1 and 2 respectively.
It does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).
Example 2:
Input: nums = [0,0,1,1,1,2,2,3,3,4]
Output: 5, nums = [0,1,2,3,4,_,_,_,_,_]
Explanation: Your function should return k = 5, with the first five elements of nums being 0, 1, 2, 3, and 4 respectively.
It does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).


# For solving this question there are 2 Approch 
1. Normal
2. HashSet (Which does not contains Duplicate elements)

1. Normal Approch 
class Solution {
    public int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
        int count = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i<nums.length; i++){
            if(i<nums.length-1 && nums[i] == nums[i+1]){
                continue;
            }else{
                nums[count] = nums[i];
                count ++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
}

âœ… What is a HashSet? HashSet is a data structure in Java that stores unique elements and provides constant time performance for add, remove, and search operations using hashing.
2. Hashset Approch TC and SC : O(n)
import java.util.*;
class Main {
    public static int removedup(int nums[]){
        HashSet<Integer> hs = new HashSet<>();
        int count = 0;
        for(int i:nums){
            if(!hs.contains(i)){
                hs.add(i);
                nums[count] = i;
                count ++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // int arr[] = {1,1,2};  // 2     nums = [1,2,_]
        int arr[] = {0,0,1,1,1,2,2,3,3,4};  // 5  nums = [0,1,2,3,4,_,_,_,_,_]
        
        System.out.println(removedup(arr));
    }
}
âœ… What is a HashSet? HashSet is a data structure in Java that stores unique elements and provides constant time performance for add, remove, and search operations using hashing.
A HashSet in Java is a collection that:
âœ” Stores unique elements only (no duplicates)
âœ” Does not maintain order
âœ” Uses a hashing mechanism internally
âœ” Provides fast operations â€” add, remove, search in O(1) average time
HashSet include in this package : import java.util.HashSet;

â“ Why Do We Use HashSet?
ğŸ”¹ 1. To Remove Duplicates
Because it automatically ignores duplicate values

HashSet<Integer> hs = new HashSet<>();
hs.add(1);
hs.add(1);
System.out.println(hs); // [1]

ğŸ”¹ 2. Fast Searching
Instead of looping through an array (O(n)), HashSet checks in O(1) time.

ğŸ”¹ 3. When Order Doesnâ€™t Matter
If we only care about unique elements and speed, HashSet is perfect.
